'''Iv<U+00E1>n Rodr<U+00ED>guez Torres''' (born [[November 30]], [[1971]], in [[Manat<U+00ED>, Puerto Rico]]), [[nickname]]d "Pudge"<ref>http://www.thebaseballpage.com/players/rodriiv01.php</ref> and "I-Rod"<ref>http://www.baseball-reference.com/r/rodriiv01.shtml</ref>, is a professional [[baseball]] player for the [[Detroit Tigers]]. Iv<U+00E1>n is considered by many to be the greatest defensive catcher ever.<ref>[http://www.pudge.org/newsArchive/20030122_stunned.htm "Marlins stunned by Pudge signing", ''MLB.com''], dated 22 January 2003, retrieved 2 February 2007</ref><ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,993113,00.html?promoid=googlep "Q & A With Pete Rose", ''Time.com''], dated 19 January 2004, retrieved 2 February 2007</ref> Although he has had the nickname "Pudge" since his youth, Rodr<U+00ED>guez was often compared early on to the veteran catcher [[Carlton Fisk]], who was also called "Pudge." Rodr<U+00ED>guez was awarded the [[American League]] (AL) [[MLB Most Valuable Player award|Most Valuable Player Award]] in [[1999 in baseball|1999]]. He ranked fourth in the AL among catchers in batting average, at .260. 

He won the World Series with the [[Florida Marlins]] in [[2003 World Series|2003]], and again reached the World Series as the starting catcher for the [[2006 Detroit Tigers season|2006 Detroit Tigers]].Rodr<U+00ED>guez has caught two [[no-hitter]]s for two different pitchers. The first one was in {{by|1994}} when he caught a [[perfect game]] by [[Kenny Rogers (baseball)|Kenny Rogers]]. The most recent one was on [[June 12]], {{by|2007}} when he caught the no-hitter thrown by [[Justin Verlander]].

==Early life==
Iv<U+00E1>n Rodr<U+00ED>guez was born in Manat<U+00ED>, and raised in [[Vega Baja, Puerto Rico]]. His father, Juan, worked for a U.S.-based construction company, and his mother, Eva Torres, was an elementary school teacher in Vega Baja.<ref name=herald>{{cite web|url=http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/2001/vol5n13/ProfilePudgeRodrig-en.html|title=Puerto Rico Profile: Ivan "Pudge" Rodriguez|publisher=Puerto Rico Herald|date=2001-03-30|accessdate=2008-03-11}}</ref> He learned baseball at an early age, his biggest rival being [[Juan Gonz<U+00E1>lez]], who he often played against in his youth.<ref name=herald/> He attended Lino Padron Rivera High School, where he was discovered by scout Luis Rosa. Rosa said of him, "He showed leadership at 16 that I<U+2019>d seen in few kids. He knew where he was going."<ref name=herald/> Rodr<U+00ED>guez signed a contract with the Texas Rangers in July 1988, at the age of 16, and began his professional baseball career.<ref name=herald/>

==Playing career==
===Minor leagues===
Rodr<U+00ED>guez made his professional debut in 1989 at the age of 17 as catcher for the Gastonia Rangers of the South Atlantic League.  In his first game, Rodr<U+00ED>guez went 3-for-3 against Spartanburg. Playing in the [[Florida State League]] in {{by|1990}}, Rodr<U+00ED>guez was selected the best catcher in the league and named to the all-star team. He placed 15th in the league in batting at .287, and led his team in [[runs batted in]], with 55. He also played in the [[Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League]] (LBPPR) over the offseason.<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=1990 |title= Career biography (1990) |accessdate=2007-12-29 |format= |work= }} </ref>

===Major Leagues===
====1991-1993====
When Rodr<U+00ED>guez made his major league debut with the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] on [[June 20]], [[1991 in baseball|1991]], he became the youngest person to catch in a major league game that season.<ref>[http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL_1991_t.shtml "1991 American League Expanded Leaderboards", ''baseball-reference.com''], retrieved 2 February 2007</ref> He immediately established himself as an excellent hitter who was also proficient in throwing out would-be [[stolen base|base-stealers]]. In fact, no other catcher in the past 35 years has been as successful at this aspect of the game, with Rodr<U+00ED>guez throwing out 48% of attempted basestealers through May 2006, far more than the runner-up during this period, the late [[Thurman Munson]].<ref>[http://bb_catchers.tripod.com/catchers/stolen_bases.htm "Encyclopedia of Baseball Catchers - Stolen Bases", "bb_catchers.tripod.com''], retrieved 30 September 2007</ref> He started many of the Rangers games at the end of the season, including 81 of the last 102. Rodr<U+00ED>guez became the youngest player in the history of the Texas Rangers to hit a [[home run]], on [[August 30]], [[1991 in baseball|1991]] in a game facing the [[Kansas City Royals]]. He hit the home run off of right-hander [[Storm Davis]]. He was named to the Major League Baseball (MLB) Rookie all-star team by both [[Topps]] and [[Baseball America]] and finished in fourth place in the American League Rookie of the Year voting. He also placed first in throwing out runners, catching 48.6% of runners attempting to steal.<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=1991 |title= Career biography (1991) |accessdate=2007-12-29 |format= |work= }} </ref> 

In [[1992 in baseball|1992]], Rodr<U+00ED>guez started 112 games behind the plate and was the youngest player in the major leagues for the second year in a row. Playing in the Puerto Rico Winter League, he had a .262 [[batting average]] playing in 17 games for Mayaguez.<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=1992 |title= Career biography (1992) |accessdate=2007-12-29 |format= |work= }} </ref> In the [[1993 in baseball|1993]] season, Rodr<U+00ED>guez batted .273, had 66 [[runs batted in]] and hit 10 home runs, ranking fourth, fifth, and fifth on his team respectively. He had a stretch of eight straight hits over two games facing the Kansas City Royals on [[July 26]] and [[July 28]]. He played the final month of the regular season in the Puerto Rican Winter league, where he had a .425 batting average and 14 runs batted in for Mayaguez. Rodr<U+00ED>guez was named to the Puerto Rican Winter League all-star team and was also the league Most Valuable Player (MVP).<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=1993 |title= Career biography (1993) |accessdate=2007-12-29 |format= |work= }} </ref>

====1994-1997====
In [[1994 in baseball|1994]], Rodr<U+00ED>guez led the American League in batting average among catchers, at .298. He placed high on his team in many statistics, placing second in batting average (.298), tied for third in doubles (19), and fourth in hits, total bases, runs, home runs, walks, games, and at bats. Rodr<U+00ED>guez played in the Puerto Rican Winter League over the winter, but he suffered a severe knee injury which kept him on the bench for the rest of the season.<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=1994 |title= Career biography (1994) |accessdate=2007-12-29 |format= |work= }} </ref> Playing for the Rangers during the [[1995 in baseball|1995]] season, Rodriguez led his team in batting, total bases, and doubles, at .303, 221, and 32 respectively. He was names the Texas Rangers' player of the year. Rodriguez also had his first multi-home run game while playing the [[Boston Red Sox]] on [[July 13]], hitting both off of all-star pitcher [[Roger Clemens]]. He also played for Caguas in the Puerto Rican Winter League during the offseason.<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=1995 |title= Career biography (1995) |accessdate=2007-12-29 |format= |work= }} </ref> 

In 1996, Rodr<U+00ED>guez set an MLB record for most doubles by a catcher, amassing 44 doubles over the course of the season. This broke the previous mark of 42 set by [[Mickey Cochrane]] in [[1930 in baseball|1930]]. He also set the major league record for at-bats by a catcher in a single season, with 639, which surpassed [[Johnny Bench]]'s record of 621 in [[1970 in baseball|1970]]. He led the Texas Rangers in doubles, at bats, hits, and runs scored. He was selected to the Major League Baseball All-Star team that played a series in [[Japan]] against the Japanese all-stars after the season was over. He again played in the Puerto Rican Winter League this season.<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=1996 |title= Career biography (1996) |accessdate=2007-12-29 |format= |work= }} </ref> In the 1997 season, he also placed first among catchers in many categories in Major League Baseball. These categories were hits, runs, runs batted in, and doubles. He placed second in home runs among catchers, below only [[Sandy Alomar, Jr.]] of the [[Cleveland Indians]], who had 20 home runs. He appeared on the cover of [[Sports Illustrated]] on the week of August 4. This marked the fourth time a player from the Texas Rangers had been on the cover of Sports Illustrated. He played in the Puerto Rican Winter League yet again, where he had a .285 [[batting average]], 4 home runs, and 18 [[runs batted in]] over the course of 32 games playing for Caguas.<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=1997 |title= Career biography (1997) |accessdate=2007-12-29 |format= |work= }} </ref>

====1998-1999====
In the [[1998 in baseball|1998]] season, Rodr<U+00ED>guez led the Texas Rangers in batting average at .325, which placed eighth in the [[American League]]. He also had 75 multi-hit games and 186 hits, finishing seventh and ninth in MLB respectively. He finished second on the Rangers in hits, total bases, triples, total bases, and [[slugging percentage]]. Rodr<U+00ED>guez was third on the team in doubles, [[home runs]], and [[stolen base]]s, and fourth in runs batted in. He had his 1000th in a game facing the [[Cleveland Indians]] on May 10 of that season. Rodriguez also became the first catcher in the history of Major League Baseball to have two or more seasons with 40 or more doubles. He was selected to the American League All-Star Team again, and he was also named to all-star teams by the [[Associated Press]], [[The Sporting News]], and [[Baseball America]].<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=1998 |title= Career biography (1998) |accessdate=2007-12-30 |format= |work= }} </ref> 

In 1999, Rodr<U+00ED>guez was selected American League MVP by Major League Baseball. That season, he set a new record for home runs in a single season among catchers, with 35. This record was later broken by [[Javy L<U+00F3>pez]] of the [[Atlanta Braves]] in 2003, who hit 42.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.baseball-almanac.com/recbooks/rb_hr2.shtml|title= Baseball Almanac home run records|accessdate=2007-12-30 |format= |work= }}</ref> Rodr<U+00ED>guez was also the first catcher to have more than 30 home runs, 100 runs batted in, and 100 runs scored in the history of Major League Baseball. In additon, he holds the distinction of being the first catcher in the history of the league to amass more than 20 home runs and 20 [[stolen base]]s. From [[May 8]], [[1999 in baseball|1999]] to [[June 1]], [[1999 in baseball|1999]], Rodr<U+00ED>guez had a career high 20 game [[hitting streak]]. He had 25 [[stolen base]]s, which was fifth most in the history of the league. He led the league in times grounded into a [[double play]], with 31. Rodriguez was only the ninth catcher in the history of Major League Baseball to win the Most Valuable Player award, and he was the first to win it since [[Thurman Munson]] in [[1976 in baseball|1976]]. He was named on all of the ballots, getting seven first place votes and six second place votes. Rodr<U+00ED>guez was the sixth [[Puerto Rico|Puerto Rican]] to win the award, and the fourth player from the Texas Rangers to win it. He also won the [[Silver Slugger Award]] for the sixth time in a row and was selected Most Valuable Player by [[Baseball Digest]]. He was again named to all-star teams by the [[Associated Press]], [[The Sporting News]], and [[Baseball America]].<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=1999 |title= Career biography (1999) |accessdate=2007-12-30 |format= |work= }} </ref>

====2000-2002====

In [[2000 in baseball|2000]], Rodr<U+00ED>guez appeared in just 91 games, which was the fewest that he appeared in since his first season in the league, [[1991 in baseball|1991]]. On July 24, Rodr<U+00ED>guez suffered a season-ending injury in a game against the [[Anaheim Angels]]. While trying to make a throw to second base, his thumb made contact with the swing of [[Mo Vaughn]]'s bat. He fractured his right thumb and underwent surgery the next day. This injury caused him to miss the rest of the season. Even though he was injured, he was still named to the second-team of the Baseball America Major League Baseball All-Star Team.<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=2000 |title= Career biography (2000) |accessdate=2007-01-17 |format= |work= }} </ref> Rodr<U+00ED>guez returned to full action in [[2001 in baseball|2001]] and had another all-star season. He was selected to his ninth straight [[MLB All-Star Game]] in a row, which tied the all time record set by [[Johnny Bench]]. He also tied Bench's record of ten straight Rawlings Gold Glove Awards in a row. He batted .308, making 2001 his seventh straight season with a batting average of over .300. He had 25 home runs, 136 hits, and 65 runs batted in.<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=2001 |title= Career biography (2001) |accessdate=2007-01-17 |format= |work= }} </ref>
Rodr<U+00ED>guez's final year with the Texas Rangers came in 2002. His .314 batting average was seventh best among American League players. This was his eighth season in a row with batting average of .300 or above. He also had 32 doubles, 2 triples, and 60 runs batted in while playing in 108 games for the Rangers. Rodr<U+00ED>guez was placed on the [[disabled list]] on [[April 23]] after suffering a [[herniated disk]] on April 15. The injury did not require surgery, and he rehabilitated while playing for class A Charlotte. He later returned to the Rangers and played there for the remainder of the season. When his contract with Texas ran out following the [[2002 in baseball|2002]] season, Rodr<U+00ED>guez signed with the [[Florida Marlins]] for one year. By then a major-league veteran of over a decade, he helped lead the young team to victory in the [[2003 World Series|World Series]].<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=2002 |title= Career biography (2002) |accessdate=2007-01-24 |format= |work= }} </ref>

====2003====
Rodr<U+00ED>guez's played his first and only season with the [[Florida Marlins]] in [[2003 in baseball|2003]]. Over the off-season, he was signed to a one year deal with the Marlins after his contract expired with the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], and he opted out of the contract for [[free agent|free agency]]. During the 2003 regular season, he set many Marlins single season records for a catcher, such as batting average, at .297, and runs batted in, at 85. On March 31, Rodr<U+00ED>guez became the tenth Marlins player ever to hit a home run on the team's first game of the season. On April 8, he set a Marlins single game record by drawing five walks in a game against the [[New York Mets]]. He had a career high nine game [[hitting streak]] from June 24 to July 2, during which he batted .500 with seven doubles, two triples, and four home runs. From June 24 to July 1, he drove in a run for eight consecutive games, another single season record for the Florida Marlins. In the post-season, he led the Marlins to their second World Series title and was named [[National League Championship Series]] [[Most Valuable Player]] for the first time in his career. He chose not to return to the Marlins the following season, and he later signed with the [[Detroit Tigers]] over the offseason.<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=2003 |title= Career biography (2003) |accessdate=2007-01-25 |format= |work= }} </ref>

====2004-present====

[[Image:Ivan Rodriguez at bat.jpg|thumb|250px|Iv<U+00E1>n Rodr<U+00ED>guez at bat on July 11, 2005]]
On [[2004 in baseball|2004]], he was selected to the [[MLB All-Star Game]] for the eleventh time in his career and for his tenth time as a starting player, joining Johnny Bench and [[Mike Piazza]] as the only Major League Baseball catchers to start an all-star game ten times or more in their career. He also won his eleventh consecutive Rawlings Gold Glove Award, making him the first player on the Detroit Tigers to win the award since [[Gary Pettis]] won it in [[1989 in baseball|1989]]. He won his seventh career Silver Slugger Award, tied with [[Victor Martinez]] of the [[Cleveland Indians]]. He was fourth in the [[American League]] in batting average and fourth among all Major League Baseball catchers. On October 1, he recorded his 1,000th career RBI in a game against the [[Tampa Bay Devil Rays]].<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=2004 |title= Career biography (2004) |accessdate=2007-01-27 |format= |work= }} </ref>  The [[2005 in baseball|2005]] season was another all-star year for Rodr<U+00ED>guez. He was selected to the Major League Baseball All-Star Game for the twelfth time in his career, and he participated in the [[Century 21 Home Run Derby]] on the day before the all-star game. In the home run derby, he finished second to [[Bobby Abreu]] of the [[Philadelphia Phillies]]. By the end of the season, he batted .276 with 14 home runs and 50 runs batted in.<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=2005 |title= Career biography (2005) |accessdate=2007-01-31 |format= |work= }} </ref> On [[October 26]], [[2005 in baseball|2005]], Major League Baseball named him the catcher on their [[Latino Legends Team]]. 

In [[2006 in baseball|2006]], Rodr<U+00ED>guez returned to throwing out runners attempting to steal a base at a very high percentage, as he did in his earlier career; he was first in the league in this category, throwing out 45.7% of all runners attempting to steal a base.<ref> {{cite web |url= http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=121358&y=2006 |title= Career biography (2006) |accessdate=2007-01-31 |format= |work= }} </ref> On [[May 9]], [[2006]], Rodr<U+00ED>guez played [[first base]] for the Tigers.  That game, a 7&ndash;6 loss to the [[Baltimore Orioles]], was the first time that he played a position other than catcher in his 1,914 Major League games.<ref>[http://detroit.tigers.mlb.com/NASApp/mlb/news/article.jsp?ymd=20060509&content_id=1445221&vkey=news_det&fext=.jsp&c_id=det Kerzel, Pete, "Notes: Pudge nudged to first", ''MLB.com''] dated 9 May 2006, URL retrieved 6 March 2007</ref> On [[August 15]], [[2006 in baseball|2006]], he also made his first Major League appearance at second base after regular second baseman [[Pl<U+00E1>cido Polanco]] was injured in a game in Boston. On [[April 16]], [[2007]], he batted in 6 runs on the way to a 12&ndash;5 victory over the [[Kansas City Royals]].  In 2007, Rodriguez walked only 1.8% of his plate appearances, the lowest percentage in the major leagues.<ref>[http://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=1&season=2007 Baseball Leaderboard |Fan Graphs<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> On October 9, the Tigers announced that they were picking up the fifth-year, 13-million-dollar option on Rodr<U+00ED>guez's contract, keeping him in a Tiger uniform through at least the 2008 season.  The team could have bought out the option for three million dollars and allowed him to become a [[free agent]].

===World Baseball Classic===
Rodr<U+00ED>guez represented [[Puerto Rico national baseball team<U+200E>|Puerto Rico]] in the [[2006 World Baseball Classic]]. He was part of a team that was mostly consisted of Major League Baseball players, among whom were [[Carlos Beltr<U+00E1>n]], [[Javier V<U+00E1>zquez]], [[Bernie Williams]] and [[Carlos Delgado]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://ww2.worldbaseballclassic.com/2006/rosters/index.jsp?sid=t897| title=Puerto Rico Roster| publisher=Major League Baseball| accessdate=2007-12-30}}</ref> Rodr<U+00ED>guez was one of several Major League Baseball players that announced commitment to represent their native countries prior to the organization of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20051205&content_id=1275939&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb| title=WBC picture becomes clearer in Dallas| author=Barry M. Bloom| publisher=Major League Baseball| date=[[2005-12-05]]| accessdate=2007-12-30}}</ref>

== Steroid allegations  ==

In [[2005 in baseball|2005]], Rodr<U+00ED>guez was accused by former Major League Baseball player [[Jos<U+00E9> Canseco]], along with fellow Texas Ranger teammates [[Juan Gonzalez]] and [[Rafael Palmeiro]] of using sterois. Canseco stated that the players used the steroids when they were all Texas Rangers players in [[1992 in baseball|1992]]. The three players were featured in a section of Jos<U+00E9> Canseco's 2005 book, "''[[Juiced: Wild Times, Rampant 'Roids, Smash Hits, and How Baseball Got Big]]''". Rodriguez denied the allegations by Canseco. <ref>http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=1986985</ref>

==Personal life==
Early in his life, Iv<U+00E1>n's first job consisted of delivering flyers in the shopping malls in Puerto Rico.<ref name="tid-bits">{{cite web| url=http://www.pudge.org/newsArchive/personalTidBits.htm| title=Personal tid-bits| publisher=Ivan "Pudge" Rodriguez Foundation | accessdate=2007-12-29}}</ref>  Rodr<U+00ED>guez married his wife, the former Maribel Rivera, on the morning of [[June 20]], [[1991]] after being called up from triple-A by the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]].<ref name="tid-bits"/> He made his major league debut that same night, throwing out two White Sox would-be base stealers. The couple has three children.<ref name="tid-bits"/> The couple and their children divide their time living in [[Colleyville, Texas]], [[Miami, Florida]] and Puerto Rico.<ref name="tid-bits"/> In 1993, Ivan and Maribel founded the ''Ivan "Pudge" Rodriguez Foundation'' with the intended purpose of helping families in Puerto Rico, [[Dallas]] and [[Fort Worth, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.pudge.org/default.htm| title=Quick Facts About the Foundation| publisher=Ivan "Pudge" Rodriguez Foundation | accessdate=2007-12-29}}</ref> Rodriguez has also expressed that the [[Make-a-Wish Foundation]] is one of his charities of choice.<ref name="tid-bits"/>

